itation on classical dance technique that is at once a primer and an ideological treatise. Throughout his writings, Rabinowitz argues in his critical introduction, which sets Volynsky's life and work against the backdrop of the principal intellectual currents of his time, Volynsky emphasizes the spiritual and ethereal qualities of ballet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBallet dancersxHistoryxRussia (Federation)xRussia (Federation). 0aBallet dancerszRussia (Federation)xHistory. 0aBalletxHistory and criticismxRussia (Federation). 0aBalletxHistoryx20th centuryxRussia (Federation). 0aBalletzRussia (Federation)xHistory and criticism. 0aBalletzRussia (Federation)xHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Dance / Classical & Ballet.2bisacsh1 aRabinowitz, Stanley J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300142495423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300142495.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles